<div id="p892" class="blockpost rowodd firstpost">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#1&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=892#p892">2009-12-27 13:52:44</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89618">The 8472</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Azureus Developer</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3>DHT Security Measures</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>In the light of recent attacks... a short list of things we could do to improve DHT security, most of them would not be backwards compatible and thus require transition mechanisms:<br /><br /><ul style="list-style-type: disc"><br /><li>fix Node IDs to sha1(IP) or something similar and reject announces, value lists or node lists from peers having a mismatching ID (they still could read from the DHT but not write). IPv6 would be a problem here though, since you can just change IPs within your netblock until you have a suitable ID if you want to attack particular regions of the keyspace.</li><br /><li>same as above, just with HashCash instead of deriving it form the IP. Has the advantage that the node ID can stay fixed even when the IP changes and nodes don't have to discover their external IP but has the disadvantage that a few node IDs can still be chosen freely, it just makes mass-spoofing harder</li><br /><li>Change target-ID = infohash to target-ID = sha1(infohash) and encrypt + HMAC values with the infohash.<br />This makes spoofing values harder since the attacking nodes would have to learn of the infohash first.<br />It would also improve privacy a bit since just recording IDs from get_peers requests wouldn't be enough to find infohashes now, you'd have to maintain a&nbsp; sha1(infohash) -&gt; infohash lookup table obtained form other sources.<br />The MACs would increase the size of packets, thus we might need separate requests/responses for the peer lists.</li><br /><li>Make sure IPs only appeear once in a) the peer database (per torrent is sufficient) b) the routing table c) the temporary node lists generated during lookups d) in the peer lists obtained from announces</li><br /><li>Change node IDs to be 256 bits wide so that we could use Curve25519 public keys as node IDs and sign/encrypt all kinds of stuff.</li><br /></ul></p>
				</div>
				<div class="postsignature"><hr />Az dev</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

